<HEAD>Report: Iran Tried to Buy Toxins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has tried to buy poison-producing strains of fungus from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. The disclosure that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was seeking the toxins renewed concerns that the country is trying to develop a weapon from the substances, Western intelligence officials said in Sunday editions of the Times. American officials said the efforts could be part of a research program to develop a defense against biological weapons. But, an American official, speaking about the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's decision to urge the Canadians and Dutch to block the sale, said: `` There are enough bad vibes that we want to stand in the way of it We're bending over backwards to be careful.'' The Iranians were seeking to buy types of fungus found on wheat and grass that produce toxins called mycotoxins which can harm humans and animals by inhibiting the ability of cells to synthesize proteins, the newspaper said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1982 asserted that mycotoxins were used in a weapon that sprayed `` yellow rain'' on the Hmong tribespeople in <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> by communist forces. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> began trying to buy the fungus last December when a man identified in intelligence files only as Mr. <PERSON> Moallem </PERSON> got in touch with Dr. <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Schiefer </PERSON>, director of the toxicology research center at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Saskatchewan </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Schiefer </PERSON> thought it unusual because the purchase of such fungus is usually from one of many laboratories around the world and not from one scientist to another, the paper said. So <PERSON> Schiefer </PERSON> contacted the Canadian government and he subsequently declined to sell them the fungus. Soon after that, the <ORGANIZATION> Iranian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> tried to buy 11 types of fungus from the Fungus Cultures in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, the paper said. The Dutch rejected the offer.
