with Geren reaction; picks up 5th graf, `Shortly after ...'. </HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FW4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICE GRAVINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican Dr. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> will meet Democrat <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Geren </PERSON> in a runoff for a congressional replacement for <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speaker toppled by ethics charges, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth-area </LOCATION> voters decided Saturday. <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON>, host of the nationally syndicated TV health show `` 60 Second Housecall,'' garnered 21,978 ballots, or 39 percent of the vote, to 17,751 votes, or 32 percent, for <PERSON> Geren </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> lawyer and former aide to Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. That made a runoff necessary, since one candidate had to garner more than 50 percent of the vote to win. Democrat <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> came in third with 12,308 votes, or 22 percent. The remaining five candidates _ two Democrats, two Republicans and a Libertarian _ trailed far behind. The highest vote-getter of the five was Republican <PERSON> Laraine </PERSON> <PERSON> Bethke </PERSON>, who had 1,313 votes, or 2.4 percent. <PERSON> Geren </PERSON> immediately predicted a runoff victory, pointing out that Saturday's combined Democratic vote topped the total achieved by Republican candidates. `` Well, the Democrats won tonight,'' <PERSON> Geren </PERSON> said at a victory party in west <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. `` It took us four candidates to do it, but when you total it up, we got nearly 60 percent of the vote. I call that a victory.'' Shortly after the results came in, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> endorsed <PERSON> Geren </PERSON>. `` He's a good man I think he will be a good congressman,'' said the former congressman, who had not endorsed anyone running in the special election. <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said he also would lend his support to <PERSON> Geren </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> said he was n't surprised <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> had come out for <PERSON> Geren </PERSON>, and said it was `` a formidable endorsement.'' But <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> predicted he, too, would win the runoff. Under state law, candidates from both parties run in a single special election, with a runoff between the two top vote-getters if no one gets a majority. The law requires the governor to schedule the runoff 20 to 30 days after the votes are officially counted, which usually occurs within a week of the election. In an emotionally charged referendum in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, voters approved 2-to-1 a proposal to reorganize the city council to equalize voting power between whites and minorities. The proposal received 41,456 votes to 20,823 against. Voters in the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> suburb of <PERSON> Coppell </PERSON> faced suspension of bus service at midnight Sunday after voting to withdraw from the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>. The suburbs of <LOCATION> Carrollton </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Plano </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rowlett </LOCATION> decided to keep the service. At the American Legion post where <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON>, cast ballots earlier Saturday, a steady stream of voters turned out during an overcast, 80-degree morning. Turnout had been expected to play a large part in the election because few issues divided the candidates, and many residents remained angry that they had to vote for anyone other than the popular <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. In the congressional race, <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> and <PERSON> Geren </PERSON> had been the front-runners in a recent opinion poll. Each man had his party's endorsements, but <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, who stressed a pro-choice stand on abortion, had endorsements from labor groups and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s son. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> did not endorse anyone. Also on the ballot were Democrats <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrovich </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, Republicans <PERSON> Bethke </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, and Libertarian <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckingham </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. After the 1988 election, the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> congressional delegation had 20 Democrats and nine Republicans The Democrats had a 34-year lock on the 12th District under <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, who was revered for his talents at serving constituents and bringing federal money and jobs to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, resigned his <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> seat June 30 after an ethics investigation turned up 69 instances of alleged rules violations. Democrats went into the election controlling the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by an 80-seat margin, but faced embarrassment if they lost in a district where registered Democrats predominate. In special elections earlier this year, Democrats held a seat in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and won one in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, and Republicans held a seat in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, the 10-4-1 proposal called for expanding the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> from 11 members to 15, with 10 elected from single-member districts, four elected from overlapping `` super districts'' and the mayor elected citywide. Currently, eight members of council are elected from single-member districts and three _ including the mayor _ are elected at large. Proponents said the plan would give minorities a greater voice in city government. Opponents said it would dilute minority voting power. Others said the plan would n't substantially change the ethnic makeup of council districts. The transit referendum on whether five <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> suburbs would withdraw from <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> bus service could affect the long-range fate of a $ 2.45 billion plan to crisscross the metropolitan area with 66 miles of light rail by 2010. The plan also called for 18 miles of rail connecting downtown to the <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and 37 miles of bus and car pool lanes for suburban commuters. Opponents said the plan would cost the suburbs a lot more than the bus service would be worth.
