<HEAD>Navigation Satellite Launch Postponed by Lightning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lightning forced the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> early Sunday to postpone the launch of a military navigation satellite for the fourth time in a week. As rain fell on the launch pad and lightning crackled nearby, the countdown on the Delta rocket continued down to the 4-minute mark and was held there as officials hoped for a break in the weather. The launch team had only a 21-minute period starting at 2:11 a.m. in which to place the Navstar satellite into a desired 11,000-mile-high orbit. When the weather did not clear in time, the effort was called off. The official reason for the scrub was `` lightning within five miles of the launch pad.'' The launch was rescheduled for no earlier than Friday. Officials said the long delay is necessary because of other launch activity in the next week. A schedule conflict with last Tuesday's launch of space shuttle <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> and thunderstorms resulted in three earlier postponements. The $ 65 million Navstar satellite is to join a network of navigation spacecraft that can tell <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and allied military forces where they are anywhere in the world - on land, sea or in the air, and in any weather. The satellite is the third of 21 improved <PERSON> Navstars </PERSON> that the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> plans to orbit to complete a global system by 1992. The first two were launched in February and June.
