<HEAD>Space Shuttle Lands Safely In California After Secret Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4-7th grafs, bgng `Earlier, sonic...', with 5 grafs to
UPDATE with inspection, a few tiles missing, and to recast. Picks up 8th
graf pvs, `The weather...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Space shuttle <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> swooped out of orbit and landed safely in the <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> on Sunday at the end of a secret mission in which the astronauts released a superspy satellite to photograph military targets around the globe. Air Force Col. <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, commander of the five-man crew, guided the 97-ton winged spaceship to a touchdown on a hard clay runway at 6:37 a.m. PDT after a flight that covered more than 2 million miles in five days, one hour. `` A super team and a great machine _ welcome home, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Culbertson </PERSON>, an astronaut who served as the spacecraft communicator at <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, told the crew as the spacecraft rolled down the runway after a perfect landing. After securing systems aboard the spacecraft for nearly an hour, the astronauts left the vehicle and did a walkaround inspection. They found a few of the 30,000 heat protection tiles missing, a normal condition. Then they were driven to a nearby facility for physical exams and showers. An hour before landing, <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> fired twin braking rockets to drop the shuttle out of orbit and start it on a fiery dive through the atmosphere and into this desert air base 80 miles north of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Mission Control lifted its curtain of silence to report the successful firing. `` All parties here report a good deorbit burn; all systems aboard <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> are clean,'' <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Welch </PERSON>, the control center commentator, reported. Sonic booms cracked overhead as <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> descended through a clear sky and made its sweeping approach to runway 17 on <LOCATION> Rogers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>. The weather here was ideal, with clear skies, unlimited visibility and mild temperatures. Although as many as half a million people have flocked to the desert air base to watch previous shuttles land, Sunday's touchdown was closed to the public because of the classified nature of the mission. Most news about the flight has been blacked out on <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> orders since an overhauled <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> lifted off from <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION> last Tuesday on its first flight in 3 -LCB- years. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> was allowed to make only periodic statements that spacecraft and crew were fine and to disclose the landing day and then the time. Sources close to the project said the main goal of the flight was the deployment of a sophisticated, 10-ton spy satellite designed to snap highly detailed photographs of military installations, troop movements and other targets of interest around the world. It would help the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> verify Soviet compliance with arms treaties, just as Russian satellites do over the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> confirmed Wednesday that a satellite was deployed by the astronauts during their first day in orbit, but he would n't discuss its purpose. To prepare for the trip back to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> commander <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> and pilot <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> conducted a series of tests Saturday to make certain the shuttle's computers and control jets were ready. In addition, mission specialists <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Leestma </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> stowed several experiments. Some of those tests were believed to be connected with the `` Star Wars'' missile defense project, while others involved determining how people can serve as military observers from space. <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, the oldest shuttle, last flew in January 1986, landing 10 days before the Challenger explosion that killed the crew of seven. After the accident <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> concentrated on making safety modifications to the two newer shuttles, Discovery and Atlantis, before turning attention to <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. Discovery and Atlantis each has made two space trips since flights resumed last September. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s return restored the shuttle flight to three vehicles at a time when the launch rate is increasing, with three more flights planned this year and nine in 1990. Another orbiter is being built as a replacement for Challenger and is scheduled for its first launch in early 1992.
