<SECOND>AM-Pierce-Pen Pals, Bjt,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Secretary Got Tons of Letters Seeking Favors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The elderly man decked out in his Sunday best posed proudly in the sunlight of a liquor store parking lot, hoping the new <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> secretary would see a family resemblance in that dignified profile. He wrote to <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, that his mother's maiden name, too, was <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, and she was from <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> wrote back that he was from <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, and he was sure they were n't kin. That letter was one of hundreds amassed by <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> during the eight years he served at <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. Normally, a housing secretary's government files would be packed off to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> where they would receive scant attention from historians, who would find sexier things to write about than the tenure of a man who managed to remain in obscurity throughout his time in office. But the $ 2 billion scandal of influence peddling and outright theft that pervaded the department during the <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> years has changed all that. For a time during the past couple of weeks, the crowd of reporters wanting to thumb through his files was so big the public affairs office at <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> was taking reservations. One theme comes through the 48 boxes of speeches, letters, bureaucratic jargon, `` grip' n' grin'' photographs and mind-numbing meeting minutes: Many of <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s pen pals were on the make. The vast majority wanted a job, some money, some time. They tugged at every string they could find, a chance meeting at a cocktail party, a handshake at a graduation ceremony, a family friend in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, a seat in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, a seat at the Cabinet table. `` Dear <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>,'' began the 1981 letter from the late <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, trying to boost the fortunes of the son of a deceased law partner. `` He's had a lot of experience in <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, is a GS-14, is a proven Republican, has philosophical credentials, and is the kind of fellow who ought to be brought up from the bureaucracy into policy work,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> wrote of his friend's son. While the letters were as different as the people who composed them, one thing all of the writers had in common was the probability that they would be horrified at the thought of their letters being dug out of the files by squads of chortling reporters. Finding the word `` CONFIDENTIAL'' across the top of a letter discovered in these files now has an effect entirely opposite from the one intended. Instead of `` keep this to yourself,'' it now means `` Xerox me.'' One such confidential memorandum was written in 1985 by <PERSON> Bernice </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, who at the time was director of the office of small and disadvantaged business utilization. Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> had gotten into a spat with <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, who was <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s executive assistant and now is a central figure in the investigations of influence peddling. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> himself had said that Ms. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> enjoyed power and was not reluctant about using it to flatten people in her path. While the files do not show what started the tiff, the incident that brought it to a memo-writing fury was when Ms. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> sent <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> employees to Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' office to cart away the furniture. After leading off with Ms. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>'s `` lack of sophistication and immaturity,'' Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> went on to call her a liar and say, `` I am not intimidated by your threats.'' `` It is my hope that attitudinal vindictiveness be put aside in the interest of effectively carrying out the secretary's goals and objectives,'' Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> wrote. A formal reply to Ms. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> was not found in the files, but the fact that someone had marked her errors of spelling and grammar gives some indication of what the tone must have been. Some of the papers in the files are dripping with irony, such as the note <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> sent to all <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> employees four years ago, urging them to report any `` knowledge of waste, fraud and mismanagement.'' `` The law provides broad protection from any reprisal being taken against you for making such reports, and I give you my personal assurance that I will not tolerate any such reprisal,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> wrote. On the back of <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s memo was typed a three-paragraph letter from <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kieren </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> employee from <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, who blew the whistle on wrongdoing in the department, got fired and spent 18 months in court to get his job back. `` My experience to report fraud, waste and mismanagement was a horror story that I for one do not want to experience again,'' <PERSON> Kieren </PERSON> wrote. Other letters, now viewed with the 20-20 vision of hindsight, might make their authors squirm. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> received a pair of thank-you letters from <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, both of whom have served as the agency's top investigators and have been instrumental in exposing fraud and waste in <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s department. `` I've told you previously how much I appreciated your support and backing,'' <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> wrote in thanking <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> for attending his 1985 retirement party as the department's inspector general. In his own note, <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, who succeeded <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON>, wrote that <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> made the event `` an evening neither <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> nor the others who were there will soon forget.'' Some of the paper in the files gives a glimpse of what <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> himself was like. It seems that rarely did anyone he know experience an illness or a death in the family that <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> did n't write a thoughtful note In one case he wrote a letter of condolence over the passing of `` Muffin,'' apparently a family's pet He also was mindful of the perks of his office, once inquiring as to the free use of a restored presidential yacht, and demanding in his extensive travels that he be accorded treatment befitting a member of the president's <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>. In 1987, that trait nearly provoked an international incident at <LOCATION> Dulles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, when <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s first-class reservations on a flight to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> were loused up. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> demanded an aisle seat in the first-class cabin, and an airline employee, <PERSON> Sami </PERSON> <PERSON> Asfahani </PERSON>, went aboard to find a place for the secretary to sit. `` In the course of events, Mr. <PERSON> Asfahani </PERSON> politely requested members of a <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> prince's party to rearrange their seating so that I could secure the type of aisle seat I had requested,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> wrote in a letter to the chairman of the board of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. `` Certain members of the prince's party overreacted in my opinion,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> wrote.
