<HEAD>Taiwan Shipping Company Loses Suit Against China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Chinese court has ruled against the first company from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> to sue <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, rejecting the claim that a Taiwanese ship captain was intimidated into confessing to smuggling, a pro-Beijing newspaper said Sunday. The Chinese-language newspaper <PERSON> Wen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wei </PERSON> <PERSON> Po </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Zhuhai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday upheld the action of Chinese customs officials and ordered the captain to pay $ 5,770 in court costs. On March 6, a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> patrol boat seized the 1,963-ton Taiwanese ship, Kuang Ta No. 2, near <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> while it carried 31 crew members and 4,760 cartons of cigarettes. Authorities released the ship and crew several days later after captain <PERSON> Tsai </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheng-Hsiung </PERSON> signed a confession that he was smuggling cigarettes. On April 11, the captain filed suit in <LOCATION> Zhuhai </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> port about 40 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. In the suit, the <ORGANIZATION> Kuang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> argued that the confession was signed under `` threat, tiring interrogation and the acute desire to release the ship and crew.'' It demanded $ 4.3 million in compensation and return of the confiscated cigarettes. In its decision, the court rejected the company's argument that the confession was extorted and that ship was in international waters, the paper said. The Chinese had said the ship was in Chinese waters and its crew planned to sell cigarettes to Chinese fishermen, a violation of <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> customs laws. Both the Nationalist government in <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> and the Communist government in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> have claimed to be the sole legitimate ruler of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since 1949, when Communist forces drove the Nationalists from the Chinese mainland. Recently, the two countries have relaxed restrictions on Taiwanese visiting <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.
