<SECOND>AM-NIreland-Liberties, Bjt,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Liberties: Among The Casualties Of Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Behind the lives destroyed in 20 years of violence in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> lies another casualty: the corruption of civil liberties in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> itself. In its attempts to crush the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, a nation that ranks among the world's older democracies has adopted laws which opponents say would look more at home in a dictatorship. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> defends the practice of detaining suspects for a week without charging them or banning British radio and television stations from broadcasting interviews with <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> members as part of the price for fighting terrorism. `` To beat off your enemy in a war you have to suspend some of your civil liberties for a time,'' she said after last October's imposition of the broadcast ban, which also covers members and sympathizers of 10 other militant groups `` None of us can be neutral as between the terrorist and the law-abiding citizen,'' added Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, who survived an <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> hotel bombing in 1984 that killed five people, including two senior <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> figures. Her critics, however, detect a gradual warping of democratic freedoms since `` the troubles'' flared and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> dispatched troops on Aug. 14, 1969 to keep <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s Protestants and Catholics apart. Twenty years later, the troops remain. The Financial Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, in an editorial in December, commented on `` a lengthening list of recent government decisions each of which has given greater weight to reasons of state than to the civic rights of the individual. Most, but not all, arise from the troubles in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>.'' However, the most controversial legislation, the Prevention of Terrorism Act, is a legacy of a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> government _ enacted in 1978 after 21 civilians were killed by an <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> bomb in an English pub. The act, which applies throughout what is known formally as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, includes police powers to detain suspects for up to a week without charge. In the decade of rule by Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s Conservative government, <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s death toll climbed past 2,700 and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has been cited 21 times _ the most by any country _ for violating the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. Her government imposed the broadcast ban on paramilitary groups and limited, or proposed limiting, the right of a suspect to remain silent. Since last fall, courts in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> have been able to interpret an accused's silence after arrest as an indication, in some circumstances, of guilt. Those circumstances are: _ Failing to mention during interrogation any fact offered in defense at trial. _ Refusing to be sworn or answer questions at trial. _ Failing to explain any possessions or marks on the defendant's clothing or person at the time of arrest _ Failing to give an account for being at a particular place at the time of arrest. The courts themselves, which are convened without juries which might be intimidated or split along sectarian lines, are also an extraordinary step taken in 1973 to combat terrorism. Last month, a government advisory panel proposed limiting the right of silence for ordinary criminals in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>. Regulations under the anti-terrorist act have been used to compel photographers and television stations to hand over material to help police investigations. TV networks complained their crews were put in added danger after being compelled last year to hand over unscreened footage of an <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> funeral march in which two British soldiers were murdered by a mob. `` We'd been pushed another step down a road with an uncertain ending,'' commented <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON>, an executive with <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Thames </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> station, after giving police tape of an interview with a suspected terrorist. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s run-ins with the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> are partly due to the fact that this country has no written bill of rights or constitution and thus issues are automatically transferred to the court in <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, instead of being filtered through domestic courts. Last November, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> refused to implement a ruling by the 19-judge court that the anti-terrorism act's detention powers violate the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> and should be repealed. The case was brought by four <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> men who were held for between 4 -LCB- days and a week in 1984 and then released. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> invoked an article of the convention that says the ruling need not be accepted `` in time of war or public emergency threatening the life of the nation.''
