<HEAD>Israel, Soviet Union Create First Joint Enterprise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In another sign of improving Israeli-Soviet relations, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> have signed an agreement to create a joint agricultural company, officials said Sunday. The announcement, carried by <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>, came one day after the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported the two countries had agreed on their first joint venture, which will make medical equipment. <PERSON> Amram </PERSON> <PERSON> Olmert </PERSON>, director of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s government-run Agrideb company, expressed hope that the new farm sector company, <PERSON> Agromir </PERSON>, would help solve the Soviet food crisis. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> cut diplomatic ties with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to protest its occupation of territories belonging to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> allies in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. But cultural and tourism exchanges have expanded since the two countries exchanged interest offices in 1987 and 1988. <PERSON> Olmert </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s advanced agricultural technology contributed to the Soviet desire `` to cooperate on a concrete, business basis, without any political implications.'' The radio reported that the agreement was signed Saturday at the end of a 12-day visit by a five-member delegation from the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, which surveyed Israeli agricultural techniques. <LOC