<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Beatlemania Bjt   08-13 0937</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Beatlemania, Bjt,0974</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beatlemania is Back in the U.S.S.R.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NXJ2</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINGRAD, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Up a grimy staircase, through a dim hallway and into a fourth-floor apartment, the Beatles are playing and <PERSON> Kolya </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON> is preaching to a new generation the Beatles gospel he accepted a quarter-century ago. From long ago and far away, the Beatles have had a grip on Soviet youth, many of whom have lost faith in government and been denied free access to religion. `` In your country, rock' n' roll is just music,'' 19-year-old <PERSON> Dima </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasiliev </PERSON>, a budding guitarist, told an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> reporter. `` Here it's our soul, our heart. If there were n't rock and roll, I'd be a Young Pioneer or Komsomol member,'' he said, referring to <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> youth groups. `` The Beatles and what they did had a special effect on <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON>, 43, who describes himself as the Fab Four's biggest Soviet fan and a `` Beatleologist. With his long black beard, he could be mistaken for a Russian Orthodox priest but for the <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> T-shirt he wears. `` Here, in a spiritual hunger, it's indescribable. It's a substitute for religion,'' he said. Memorabilia is everywhere in <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON>'s single grubby room, his part of an apartment shared with two other families. It is a shrine, museum, dining room, living room and bedroom all in one. Shelves from ceiling to floor are filled with Beatles books and buttons. Walls are lined with `` A Hard Day's Night'' and `` Yellow Submarine'' posters and portraits of <PERSON> John </PERSON>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, <PERSON> George </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ringo </PERSON>. Like an eternal flame, a lamp atop the bookshelf continuously throws orange light onto a photograph of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>, who was murdered in 1980. A small sign in front reads in English, `` Bless You.'' <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON>'s proudest possession is a red, white and blue soccer jersey he says <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON> wore. He said he got it through a friend of singer <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Baez </PERSON>. About a dozen teen-agers are sitting around a table as Beatles music blares from a tape recorder. `` What's the name of that song?'' <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON> demands of one. The boy shrugs his shoulders. `` I'll have to call your mother about that tomorrow,'' <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON> says jokingly. <PERSON> Vasiliev </PERSON> calls <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON> his spiritual father who `` taught us that there's more than what school and parents taught us.'' The teen-agers come by regularly to sing, dance and talk music. <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON> takes his Beatlemania seriously. He's been at it for 25 years, since a friend played him a tape recorded off <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> radio. `` Something happened,'' he recalled. `` The words used were the best. It was a high. Like God, sacred. A love hit me which I did n't have before, only love for my mother. <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON>, a painter, made himself an expert on Beatles trivia. He collected more than 15,000 Beatles photos, all of their albums, bootlegged recordings and every scrap of paper about them he could find. As `` I Saw Her Standing There,'' `` Help,'' and `` Norwegian Wood'' resounded, he showed a reporter two Beatles `` encyclopedias'' he painstakingly compiled, including newspaper clippings, photographs and poetry by or about the Beatles. Two articles serve as reminders that Beatles music and the lifestyle they represented once were officially frowned on. `` These bugs can swiftly ignite the very darkest and primitive passions,'' the satirical magazine <PERSON> Krokodil </PERSON> wrote in 1964. In the same year, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Composers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> titled his condemnation of the Beatles in Literary Gazette, `` From the <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bees </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Dung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bugs </ORGANIZATION>.'' Beatles records were banned, but <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beatles </LOCATION> fans found other sources: foreign radio broadcasts and smuggled albums. Still, just listening was n't enough. By 1966, he recalled, `` People you would meet on the street talked not about their illnesses or studies. The subject was the Beatles. They were also the main subject of telephone calls.'' The group's music spawned dozens of copycat groups in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and gave birth to original Soviet rock, such as the group Aquarium, which recently signed a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> recording contract and whose lead singer, <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Grebenshchikov </PERSON>, credits the Beatles with changing his life. Fans held Beatles festivals, swapped tapes and photos, bought their albums for exhorbitant prices on the black market, and some sported their familiar haircuts and dressed like them in jackets with round collars and no lapels. <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON> says some were arrested for `` hooliganism'' and `` anti-social behavior.'' One teen-ager at <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON>'s apartment said police fined his father for playing Beatles music too loudly. The first positive press report about the group appeared in 1968, and <PERSON> Vasin </PERSON> recalls in a Soviet rock history book titled `` Back in the U.S.S.R.'' that he was so happy he ran around <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> with the article in his hand shouting, `` We've won!'' More than two decades after they rocketed to the top of Western music charts, the Beatles began to receive official recognition here. The state record company <ORGANIZATION> Melodia </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 issued `` A Taste of Honey'' and `` A Hard Day's Night.'' Some singles had been released earlier without mentioning the group's name, because <ORGANIZATION> Melodia </ORGANIZATION> did n't legally obtain permission to distribute them Soviet Beatlemania has not gone unnoticed by the people who made the music. In November, <PERSON> Melodia </PERSON> released `` Back in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION>,'' a collecton of old rock' n' roll songs <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> recorded exclusively for <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> fans. He also paid tribute to them in January in a phone-in show on the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> service. He said he would like to perform in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and that he admired <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> fans for following the Beatles despite official harassment. `` It did n't put us off, Russians. We love you madly,'' he said.
