of all, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, he said. <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> agreed. `` It's fairly prudent for a senator to run a decent amount of TV. Secondly, think about what percentage of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population is within those media markets. He's going to get a piece of the country in terms of 1992,'' <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> has opted to be safe and at the same time leave his political options open. `` Politicians always run scared, assume the worst and prepare for it,'' said <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>. `` Therefore, you raise money if you're able to as a way of discouraging whatever potential opposition may surface and being ready to wage a serious campaign if you need to.'' Looking at <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s ability to raise $ 4.3 million toward 1990, <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said: `` All of it fits in well with a potential run for the presidency in 1992 or 1996 in any case. It seems very sensible even if he has n't decided if he's going to do that.''
