<SECOND>AM-Woodstock-Woolstock,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woolstock Not So Keen on Woodstock `Copy' Party, But Sponsor Undaunted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER MUNNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of little Woolstock, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, say they're not about to allow a concert in the town park on the anniversary of the <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION> rock festival because they're worried about drugs and undesirables. But the radio station sponsoring the event said the show will go on whether the city likes it or not, on private land if need be. And besides, how many undesirables are going to show up at supper time on a week night? Even if there are free hot dogs? The City Council in the north-central <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> town of 230 people voted 4-1 Friday to prohibit radio station <ORGANIZATION> KRIT </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dodge </LOCATION>, about 20 miles from <LOCATION> Woolstock </LOCATION>, from holding a two-hour concert at the park Tuesday night to observe the 20th anniversary of <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION>. In 1969, a long list of leading rock groups attracted more than 500,000 people to a dairy farm in the Catskills of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> state </LOCATION>, actually about 45 miles from <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION>. KRIT officials said they were inspired to hold the concert because <LOCATION> Woolstock </LOCATION> is just a letter away from <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION>, but despite that similarity they said the town really does n't have to fear it will be overrun. Woolstock officials said they did n't want to take a chance. `` We're not an anti-social town,'' said Councilman <PERSON> Norval </PERSON> <PERSON> Story </PERSON>, who voted with the majority. `` We like to have these gatherings. But we were kind of concerned about the element that might come in. The drug problem is bad enough as it is.'' Story and Woolstock Mayor <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Spellmeyer </PERSON> said the event could have been sponsored at the park if <ORGANIZATION> KRIT </ORGANIZATION> had given the town a little time to plan. Instead, they said, town officials learned of the event in newspaper accounts last week. `` I think they're blowing it up a little,'' said <ORGANIZATION> KRIT </ORGANIZATION> news director <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Alberts </PERSON>. `` Look, it's from 6 to 8 p.m., no alcohol will be allowed and it's in a fairly remote area on a Tuesday night, so you're not going to have that many people,'' she said. Instead of <LOCATION> Jimi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hendrix </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Crosby </LOCATION>, Stills, <PERSON> Nash </PERSON> and <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, the musical talent is <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Dohrmann </PERSON> of <PERSON> Barnum </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lind </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dodge </LOCATION>, both guitarists. `` They're the most wholesome guys in the whole world,'' Ms. <PERSON> Alberts </PERSON> said. `` Sure, there will be music from the'60s and a sound system, but there wo n't even be any drums.'' `` And there ca n't be all that many people. If anybody has to work the next day, they certainly are n't going to drive too far. It's Tuesday night, after all.'' However, there will be the attraction of free hot dogs and soft drinks, courtesy of KRIT. <PERSON> Dorhmann </PERSON> does not have a telephone listing and no one answered the telephone at <PERSON> Lind </PERSON>'s residence. As for the failure to notify town officials in advance, Ms. <PERSON> Alberts </PERSON> said the radio station did n't know it needed to ask for permission. Besides, she said, the town did n't have to do anything. `` It's up to KRIT to do all the planning. It was our event. If a family were planning a reunion in the Woolstock city park, it's the family that puts it together,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Alberts </PERSON> said the radio station is determined to hold the event regardless of whether it has the blessing of the Woolstock council. `` This is going to happen no matter what,'' she said. `` Before the council met, an area farmer called us and said he suspected they would vote it down. He said we could use some of his land. `` And we got a call from a person in <LOCATION> Woolstock </LOCATION> who said he had a big lot where we could hold it.'' She said radio officials will visit the proposed sites and make a decision on where to hold the show by Monday morning.
