<HEAD>Facts and Figures on the Panama Canal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Canal Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALBOA HEIGHTS, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some facts and figures on the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> Canal:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 COST _ The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> paid the French, who started work on the canal, $ 40 million for rights and properties, then spent $ 387 million and ten years building it. VOLUME _ Nearly 262 million cubic yards of dirt and rock were removed, enough to fill a train encircling the earth four times. Dredges have dug out nearly 400 million more cubic yards to widen the canal and keep it in good condition. <ORGANIZATION> UNSUNG </ORGANIZATION> HERO _ The Bucyrus steam shovel, 95-ton behemoths that chomped out eight tons at a single scoop. The maximum number used at one time: 68. FIRST TRANSIT, OCEAN-TO-OCEAN _ A canal workboat, the crane barge <PERSON> Alexandre </PERSON> <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, Jan. 7, 1914. OFFICIAL OPENING _ Aug. 15, 1914, by the <ORGANIZATION> S.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ancon </ORGANIZATION>. PAYING TRANSITS _ More than 700,000. Total tons: more than 4 billion. AVERAGE TIME PER TRANSIT _ nine hours ocean-to-ocean. 1914 COMMERCIAL RATES _ 90 cents per cargo ton, not raised until 1974. 1989 COMMERCIAL RATES _ $ 1.83 per cargo ton; $ 1.46 per ton unloaded. HIGHEST TOLL _ $ 109,653.60 paid in May 1989 by the Star Princess, based on the amount of revenue-producing space aboard the ship. LOWEST TOLL _ 36 cents, paid by 140-pound adventurer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Halliburton </PERSON> when he swam the canal in the 1920s.
</TEXT>
