<SECOND>AM-Massachusetts Education,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Schools, Colleges, Strain Under Budget Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Deep cuts in state spending will mean larger classes, closed schools, fewer teachers and fewer sports programs for the 1 million students returning to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> public schools and colleges next month, educators say. At the state's 29 public colleges and universities, students will feel the effects of a $ 39.3 million cut in higher education funding ordered by Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The 1,800 public schools will have to shoulder their share of a $ 210 million reduction in state aid to cities and towns. Educators use words like `` disaster,'' `` tragedy,'' and `` devastation'' to describe the impact. The governor, who touted his state's booming economy during his unsuccessful presidential campaign last last year, only to be blindsided by a surge in red ink this year, expressed deep regret in announcing the cuts last month. But he said he had little choice but to carve $ 491 million out of the state's 1989-90 budget. The cuts and the withholding of funds were needed to bring the budget to $ 12.2 billion, in keeping with a balanced-budget provision in the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Constitution. Schools in communities small and large are feeling the pinch. For example: _ <LOCATION> Brockton </LOCATION> is considering a plan to charge high-school atheletes to take part in sports programs. _ The small central <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> community of <LOCATION> Belchertown </LOCATION> may begin making students pay to ride the school buses. _ <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> will have to lay off at least 300 and possibly as many as 800 teachers out of a faculty of 2,000 because of a severe budget crisis in that city. All but a few athletic programs have been cut including soccer, ice hockey and swimming, according to Assistant Superintendent <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Southworth </PERSON>. _ Some 8,000 college students _ most of whom would attended community colleges, designed to serve the poorest sector of the community _ will be turned away. `` It is a cruel blow to schools,'' state education Commissioner <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Raynolds </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said last week. `` There wo n't be a single school across the commonwealth that is intact as it was last spring.'' Higher education Chancellor <PERSON> Franklyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenifer </PERSON> said that despite a 7.7 percent tuition increase and steep hikes in student fees, the budget crisis has halted a push to advance the state's public college and university system into the nation's top rank. `` We will at best be doing worse than we were last year, and last year was a bad year,'' <PERSON> Jenifer </PERSON> said. `` We've taken the position that one maintains quality at all costs. Access to mediocrity is no access at all.'' Higher education budget cuts will translate into 1,900 canceled course sections for the 120,000 full-time students, <PERSON> Jenifer </PERSON>'s staff has calculated. Some 1,200 part-time faculty and staff positions are being cut, and 8,000 student slots, most in community colleges, were eliminated for the fall term. No one will be turned away from public elementary and secondary schools. But because of faculty and staff cuts, some of the 824,000 public school students will be in bigger classes than before. Staff and faculty reductions at public schools across the state are expected to reach 8,000, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, a parents group and the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> have gone to court to block a plan to close six public schools and consolidate three others. `` Two years from now, people are going to be saying, ` How come our kids ca n't compete?''' said <PERSON> Rosanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacon </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're unwilling to spend our money on our kids. This is not the way they do things in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
