<HEAD>Navy Moving To Outflank Opponents Of Its Nuclear Blast Simulator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Barred from the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and hounded by environmentalists in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> now is trying to outflank its opponents as it eyes the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to test whether ship electronics can withstand a nuclear blast in space. `` We've started a very active public information and availability program on the Gulf Coast,'' said Capt. W.E. <PERSON> Mahew </PERSON>, manager of the Electromagnetic Pulse Radiation Environment Simulator For Ships -LRB- Empress II -RRB- program. `` There was too much misinformation about what the program was -LRB- when it was proposed for the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> -RRB- and we were never able to counter that information,'' he said. `` The guy who got there first and told the story first was the only who was believed.'' Empress II consists of a barge-mounted, truncated cone of antennas _ 128 feet high and 200 feet in diameter _ that surround a pulser which can simulate the electromagnetic field that would be generated by a nuclear blast in space. The system generates an electromagnetic pulse -LRB- EMP -RRB- that lasts just 10 billionths of a second, but measures 50,000 volts per meter at 100 meters from the barge in all directions. The <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> is fired at passing ships to test the effectiveness of measures designed to protect electronics systems from the <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> that would be generated by a nuclear blast in space. While the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> insists that the <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> generated by Empress II poses no risk to the environment and that exclusion zones around the barge will protect the electronic systems of nearby planes and boats, it has had a difficult time thus far making its case. `` They just have not accurately assessed the impact of this on human health, and what makes this particularly sad is that most of the people being exposed are people in the service,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimbrell </PERSON>, an attorney for the Foundation on Economic Trends. `` What we're seeing here is similar to the Army allowing those soldiers to be exposed to the first nuclear blasts -LRB- after World War II -RRB- and we know the high incidence of cancer that resulted there,'' he said. The foundation, a Washington-based watchdog group on emerging technologies, has filed suit in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> seeking to halt Empress II tests off the coast of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> until the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> adequately assesses the impact of the tests on human health and animal life and on the electronic circuitry of nearby airplanes and boats. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> began operating the Empress II off <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> in the summer of 1988 after <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> enacted legislation prohibiting it from operating in the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> until the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> demonstrated that the tests could be conducted no where else with less environmental impact. After the lawsuit was filed, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> chose a new site off <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and conducted an environmental assessment that concluded the Empress II tests would have no significant environmental impact at the new site. As soon as the 30-day period for public comment on that assessment ended last month, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> resumed the Empress II tests at the new site. In the meantime, letters went out July 26 announcing that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> planned to begin the environmental assessment that could lead to a new test site for Empress II about 20 miles off the <LOCATION> Alabama-Mississippi </LOCATION> coast in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mahew </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> needs the Gulf site because weather conditions limit use of the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> site to the summer months. Originally, winter testing was to have been conducted in the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is planning 60 days of Empress II tests in the Gulf annually between October and April. Long before plans for the Gulf site were announced, however, <PERSON> Mahew </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> personnel were meeting with state and local officials and environmental groups in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> in order to `` get ahead of the opposition.'' `` We're laying it all out,'' he said. In four years of <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> and independent research on the effects of <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION>, he argues, `` We've never been able to demonstrate any harm to human health, we've never been able to demonstrate any harm to marine biota Despite those claims, and despite its best public relations efforts, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> appears to be facing a long legal battle before it can pursue its plan for year-round Empress II tests in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and the Gulf. `` I'm not an expert in the politics of the region,'' <PERSON> Kimbrell </PERSON> said when asked to assess the prospects of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> winning the public acceptance for Empress II in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> that eluded it in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. `` However, they wo n't have any better legal atmosphere because they're still going to have to comply with what is a federal law, the National Environmental Policy Act,'' he said.
