<HEAD>Leland: Driven by Mission to `Save One Life ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, never freed of his torment over a dying girl in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> years ago, was drawn again and again to the place he called `` the end of the Earth.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> `` Mickey'' <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, a six-term <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> Democrat and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Hunger, was on his fifth visit to refugee camps near the <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> border when the plane carrying his party crashed. The wreckage was found Sunday, six days after the plane vanished after taking off in bad weather from <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> capital, and heading for the Fugnido refugee camp, 480 miles southwest. Although there were no immediate positive identifications of the bodies found by paramedics dropped from a helicopter, rescuers said no one could have survived the fiery crash. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> quickly expressed condolences to the 44-year-old congressman's wife as well as to the families and friends of those `` who died with him'' on what the president called a `` noble cause.'' It was in 1985 when <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> recalled standing in a refugee camp 10 months earlier and asking a relief official about a little girl `` who looked to be about 70 or 80 years old _ a skeleton of a person with a thin layer of brown skin draped on her, who had just a faint breath of life in her.'' `` While I was talking to him, she died. I can see her face right now. Every day I see her face,'' <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> said at the time. Twice chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> evolved, by his own account, from a firebrand `` black activist,'' to an `` activist on behalf of humanity everywhere, whether it is in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, in any part of the world where people are desperate and hungry for the freedoms and rights they deserve as human beings.'' His deeds reflected the breadth of that concern. Just as he pressed for famine relief in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, he fought as relentlessly to feed the homeless in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He went to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to retrieve three children for their families in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Last October, he went to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, where he helped negotiate the release of three political prisoners and their families. In a bid to bridge festering hostility between black and Jewish communities, he supervised for 10 years a program under which poor black kids from <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> were sent to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for six weeks to learn about the Jewish culture and heritage. A Roman Catholic, <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> once bicycled through <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and often cited the Talmud, the Jewish commentary on the Old Testament. `` If you save one life, you save the whole world,'' was his favorite passage. `` He's someone who cared and made a difference ... a militant man who found he could change the system more from the inside than the outside,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who served with <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> on the hunger committee and thrice joined him on trips to <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. After offering that assessment of his friend, <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> to join the search. He was aboard the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> helicopter that found the wreckage. When <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> moved from the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1979, replacing the retired Rep. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, he almost immediately began pushing for a special committee on world hunger. Even after he recited the horrors he witnessed in a 1983 trip to <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, he was opposed by people who argued yet another select committee was a waste of money, and by those who viewed it as an infringement of their own turf _ foreign relations, agriculture and appropriations. <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> would n't back off. Instead, he rallied all the volunteer organizations concerned with hunger, and enlisted the help of celebrities like <PERSON> Valerie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Denver </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cliff </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>. House Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Mass., lent his prestige <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> invited members of the established committees to join his unofficial caucus on hunger. Finally, in the spring of 1984, he got his committee _ and the momentum that resulted in $ 800 million for famine relief the following fiscal year. He personally convinced President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to divert a ship loaded with food to <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. As a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on telecommunications, he repeatedly tangled with the television networks over black representation, on and off camera, in their shows. A year before <PERSON> Diahann </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrol </PERSON> and <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> appeared on `` Dynasty,'' he needled <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> executives about why the show did n't have any black characters <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> said he learned his values from his mother, a teacher who had put herself through school working as a short-order cook. As a pharmacy student at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, he joined a volunteer group which operated free health clinics. He was drawn, too, to the <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Panther </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which also operated free clinics and gave breakfasts to needy black children. His political influences ranged from <PERSON> Stokely </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmichael </PERSON>, to <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> X </PERSON>, to Tanzanian President <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyerere </PERSON>, and he eventually formed his own <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Team </ORGANIZATION>, known as the Black Cats, and helped establish three health clinics in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> conservatives assailed him a radical, an image not helped during his days in the state legislature by his seven-inch Afro, a leather shoulder bag, and his dashikis _ long since replaced by three-piece business suits. `` I never considered myself to be a radical because I fought for the rights of human beings,'' he said. In 1972, in his first race for public office, he was elected to the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION>, where he championed health issues, included a generic-drug law over the stiff lobbying of the pharmaceutical lobby. When he ran for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1978, he had no Republican opposition and defeated a <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidate with more than 96 percent of the vote. He won re-election five times with similar ease, despite a 1988 primary challenge from <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Spates </PERSON>, who charged that <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> had lost touch with constituents while seeking national exposure as spokesman for the hungry and homeless. `` There's people I've not touched in a long time,'' he acknowledged. `` I have been on the road quite a bit.'' But he earned respect even from staunch conservatives like <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>, the ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION>, who recently wrote in the <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>'s `` personal diplomacy'' with Ethiopian and Sudanese officials `` opened up life-sustaining corridors in the border region between the two countries _ a peaceful -LRB- relief -RRB- supply route.'' <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, who also served on the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, often thrust himself into the position of mediator in matters of international or inter-racial consequence. He was closer to Cuban President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> than any other member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` While I disagree with his fundamental ideology, I respect him for his intellect,'' <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> returned that sentiment, and <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> was often tapped to open avenues of communication between the <LOCATION> United </