<HEAD>Defiance Campaign to Widen as Government Reels From Power Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the government distracted by a damaging leadership struggle, anti-apartheid activists said Sunday the next phases of their nationwide defiance campaign wil include challenges to segregation of beaches and schools. The defiance campaign, launched Aug. 2 when blacks and <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> peacefully sought treatment at segregated white hospitals, has been condemned by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government as an attempt to provoke confrontation and violence. Since Friday, however, top government officials have been preoccupied by a dispute between President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> and Education Minister F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and is expected to succeed <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> after the Sept. 6 parliamentary elections. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, 73, brought the long-running rift into the open when he announced Friday he had not been consulted about de Klerk's planned meeting on Aug. 28 with Zambian President <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaunda </PERSON>, a prominent critic of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s racial policies. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> conferred with his <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> colleagues on Saturday and reportedly obtained full backing from them heading into a formal Cabinet meeting with <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> on Monday. Political writers said <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> was likely to demand that <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> stop interfering in government affairs pending his retirement next month. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> could accept the ultimatum, quit immediately, or try to fire de Klerk and other ministers, newspapers suggested. In any case, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has said he and <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </P