<HEAD>Bennett Says Drug Users, Not Government, Blame for Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drug users, rather than failed government policies, are to blame for the spread of drugs throughout society, drug policy director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said Sunday. He also defended the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's efforts to combat drugs, including former First Lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s `` Just Say No'' campaign. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> by law must forward a new national strategy for fighting drugs to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by Sept. 5. It is expected to call for a major boost in federal spending and emphasize both tougher penalties for individual drug use and mandatory treatment for addicts. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> was asked on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' `` Face the Nation'' if his approach marks a reversal from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration policy, which cut funds for treatment and emphasized drug interdiction and arrests of kingpins. The $ 21 billion spent fighting drugs during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration `` was n't wasted, and it was n't all wrong. ... `` said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>. `` There were some real successes during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> era. `` I do n't think anyone can deny that drugs are pervasive throughout much of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, but recent statistics indicate that casual drug use is down. `` Although some people like to criticize the educational efforts and the first lady's efforts, they obviously have had some effect,'' said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who as <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s education secretary published a booklet on how to keep drugs out of schools. `` We are shifting strategy, but let's remember we have not had the opportunity before to have a comprehensive look,'' said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>. `` The government may not have been as effective ... -LRB- or -RRB- as smart as it should have been. ... But it's the people who are taking drugs that are causing these tragedies, not the government,'' he said. Asked if he would recommend raising taxes for the drug fight, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> replied, `` Do n't think we need taxes.'' But he insisted, `` The money will be there. We will put our cards on the table. We will suggest what we want to do and we will propose spending more money. Then we will see what the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wants to do. `` It means making some difficult choices,'' he said. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, citing reports of bootleg sales of methadone by addicts to buy crack, said drug treatment programs need `` much more accountability.'' Without it, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> warned, `` at some point the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people will say, ` The heck with it.' `` The more I've seen of -LRB- treatment -RRB-, the more impressed I am by the need for efforts in prevention. It's terrible to get into this business, it's very hard to get out of it,'' he said. He scoffed at the notion that research can find a way to end people's cravings for drugs. `` We're not going to uncover anything in a laboratory that ... we can put in a pill and give it to somebody and they're not going to want drugs anymore,'' said the onetime philosophy professor. And despite five months of `` conscientious'' study of the issues, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said he has found `` no magic bullet.'' His recommendations wo n't be like `` Batman -LRB- coming -RRB- through the transom saying, ` Here it is, and it's over,''' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said.
