<HEAD>Protests, Escape Attempt Mark Anniversary of Berlin Wall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with protests in East Germany
and Budapest. Pick up 7th pvs, ``The August...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 West Germans vandalized the Berlin Wall, an official called for its removal, and an East German tried to escape to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> on Sunday, the 28th anniversary of the day construction began on the infamous barrier. Security forces also dispersed about 50 East Germans who tried to demonstrate in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> in front of the West German mission, which was closed last week after a crowd of East Germans arrived seeking refuge. Witnesses said the demonstrators tried to lay flowers at the mission gates in an apparent act of solidarity with their countrymen holed up inside demanding exit visas to the West. No protesters were arrested. <PERSON> Dorothee </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilms </PERSON>, the West German minister for inter-German affairs, criticized <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s effort `` to build up and perfect the inhumane barriers'' between East and West. Her deputy chief, <PERSON> Ottfried </PERSON> <PERSON> Hennig </PERSON>, predicted the wall would be taken down by the end of the century. An unidentified assailant hurled a firebomb at the wall near the Brandenburg Gate early Sunday, West German police said. The bomb exploded when it crashed against the wall, but it burned out without causing serious damage. The East German state news agency, <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION>, said several masked assailants from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> damaged border barriers in the southern sector of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. ADN, which did not describe the damage, said a diplomatic protest would be lodged with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> authorities. Witnesses at the Checkpoint Charlie border crossing between East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> reported Sunday that at least one man attempted to flee across the heavily guarded crossing just before noon. He was arrested by East German border guards before reaching Western territory, the witnesses said. In <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, 200 people gathered at downtown Voeroesmarty Square to protest the wall. The speakers, who included young East German tourists, called for its demolition. Several displayed placards with slogans proclaiming, `` Make Love, Not Wall,'' and `` We Have No Need of Any Control.'' No violence was reported during the 40-minute demonstration. The August 13th Society, a human rights organization that monitors East European refugee affairs, estimates that at least 40,000 East Germans have escaped across the borders with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> since the wall was erected. Prior to 1961, hundreds of thousands of East Germans fled to the West, draining the Communist state of many of its top scientists, artists and intellectuals. The number of escapes surged over the last few months after <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> began dismantling its border barriers with <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. East Germans can usually obtain permission to travel to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, a neighboring Communist ally, and an estimated 1,500 of them have illegally crossed from there into <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> this summer. Several hundred East Germans have recently sought refuge at West German embassies, which has prompted <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> to close its embassy in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> and its mission in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> on Saturday defended the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall and said hopes for its removal are `` illusory.'' <PERSON> Neues </PERSON> <PERSON> Deutschland </PERSON>, the newspaper of the <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said the wall is `` a step toward peace'' and that it will remain in place to prevent East Germans from fleeing to the West.
