<HEAD>New Junta Announces Economic Reform Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s new military leaders on Sunday announced an economic reform program that includes a 20 percent cut in government spending and possible decreases in government subsidies of consumer goods. Col. <PERSON> Salah </PERSON> <PERSON> Din </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Karrar </PERSON>, a member of the 15-member council in charge of the economy, said in an interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> that he was optimistic <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> would be able to reach a loan agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> soon. Improving <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s faltering economy, which is burdened by a $ 13 billion foreign debt and an exhausting civil war in the south, has been one of the main targets of the new regime, which took power in a military coup June 30. <PERSON> Karrar </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> had ordered government units to cut spending by 20 percent, but he did not specify how much money that would save. One of the junta's first acts was to cut the Cabinet from 30 to 22 ministers. <PERSON> Karrar </PERSON> also said that government subsidies to some of the main consumer goods would be `` reconsidered,'' but he did not say which commodities would be affected. The ousted elected government of <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON> had budgeted $ 183 million for subsidies this fiscal year. <PERSON> Karrar </PERSON> said he was optimistic <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> would reach agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> next month without affecting the welfare of Sudanese people. He gave no details. In February 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> declared <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> ineligible for further loans for defaulting on debt payments. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic assistance was halted in January because the <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> government was late in paying off loans.
