<HEAD>Investigators Wonder If Crack Smoke Killed 10 Infants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Medical examiners in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> are trying to determine whether 10 infants died over the last three years as a result of inhaling secondhand crack smoke from adults. The 10 all had chemical evidence of cocaine in their blood. The coroner, <PERSON> Haresh </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirchandani </PERSON>, came up with the theory after the April 6 death of a 10-month-old girl named <PERSON> Tasha </PERSON>. Testing showed there was cocaine in the her blood, some of which had gotten there the night before her death. <PERSON> Mirchandani </PERSON> said the baby died after apparently inhaling smoke from crack, a highly addictive form of cocaine, generated by her mother and other adults in the house. The deaths of <PERSON> Tasha </PERSON> and nine other babies might show, according to the medical examiner's theory, that children are highly susceptible to serious illness and death from breathing in crack smoke when the drug is smoked by adults around them. <PERSON> Mirchandani </PERSON> stressed last week that more research was needed before his theory could be proven. <PERSON> Mirchandani </PERSON>'s study involved the cases of six girls and four boys _ ranging in age from 28 days to 10 months _ who died in the city in the last three years. Each infant had either cocaine or its chemical residue in their blood, tissue, or organs, the study found. Several babies had parents, siblings, or baby sitters who used crack. Several slept in small, poorly ventilated rooms in crowded row houses. In some instances, police or residents said they saw lingering clouds of crack smoke or discarded crack vials in the homes, according to the investigation. <PERSON> Mirchandani </PERSON> said the investigation started the day after <PERSON> Tasha </PERSON>'s death He refused to provide the full names or addresses of the infants or their relatives. An autopsy performed on <PERSON> Tasha </PERSON>'s body revealed small amounts of active cocaine as well as the drug's residue. <PERSON> Mirchandani </PERSON> determined that the presence of the active cocaine, which is usually broken down by the body in two hours, showed the baby had been exposed to it shortly before she died _ `` only a few hours before death,'' <PERSON> Mirchandani </PERSON> said. The residue indicated exposure to the drug of a long-term nature, he said. <PERSON> Mirchandani </PERSON> visited the baby's 22-year-old mother May 1. `` She admitted being a crack addict,'' he said. She `` said she used cocaine before and during the pregnancy.'' <PERSON> Mirchandani </PERSON> said the mother was not breast-feeding the child. She had not put the drug in the child's food or milk, and there was no sign the child could have found the drug lying around and eaten it. Recent studies of the dangers of the passive inhalation of cigarette smoke led <PERSON> Mirchandani </PERSON> to the possibility that the same was true of the passive inhalation of crack smoke. He said even though the mother `` said she did n't smoke around the baby,'' the child's room was not well-ventilated and other adults addicted to the drug smoked it in the house. Similar cases in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> supported the doctor's theory, he said. `` Cocaine can be toxic at any dose, and is proven to be dangerous and deadly in even small doses ... even in adults,'' he said. `` I would expect a much heightened toxicity for infants. It's common sense Something that is toxic for adults ... would be even more toxic for an infant.''
</TEXT>
