<HEAD>At Least a Month's More Work in Murder Investigation, Task Force
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> is a month or more away from completing a study of thousands of documents, videotapes and other possessions of a former law student called a suspect in the killings of 40 young women. `` There's more of it here than even I thought there was,'' Capt. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, commander of the <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> task force, said of the material seized from <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, 38. Asked if police had found anything to connect <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> with any of the <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> victims, <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> replied, `` Not yet.'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> denies he is the killer. `` People should know the fact that I have never hurt anyone in my life,'' he said in a statement released earlier through his attorney. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> has not been charged with any violent crimes, including the <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> killings, a series of slayings from 1982 to 1984, mostly of prostitutes in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, Ore. The case takes its name from the stream south of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> river where the bodies of the first victims were found. Police have blamed the deaths of 40 young women and the disappearance of eight others on the serial killer. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> is in the King County Jail, serving a one-year sentence for a 1979 burglary and additional time for escape. He's due to be released Sept. 25, but <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said he doubts the 12-member task force will be finished by then with analyzing the thousands of items in 55 boxes and bags taken in a July 12 search of the home of <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' parents and a rental house <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> used as a student in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>. Police would have no hold on <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> after Sept. 25, <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. `` We're still going through the paperwork and expect to be doing that for another month or so,'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. `` There's been nothing so far to diminish our interest or to indicate we should feel any more strongly about him.'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> walked away from a work-release program in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> in 1981, and was n't apprehended until January of this year, when it was learned he was living at his parents' home in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> and attending <ORGANIZATION> Gonzaga </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. Among the possessions seized by the task force were police badges and paraphernalia. Investigators have suspected the <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> killer could be a police officer or someone posing as one. In an affidavit filed to support a search warrant in the case, some people who knew <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said he liked pornography, frequented prostitutes and carried photographs of mutilated women. Among items seized in the search were 1,800 videotapes. A sample of the videotapes show they `` ranged from TV shows to hard-core pornography,'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. He said he will have the task force look at all the tapes `` only if I have to. I do n't want to, but if necessary, I will do that.'' Besides the tapes, the material includes massive amounts of paperwork, much of it receipts and personal documents. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said detectives have followed up much of their reading with interviews, but he had no estimate of the number conducted. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said investigators are seeking both possible links to the killings and alibis for <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>. `` We're working very, very hard to prove that he's someone not of interest to us,'' he said. Detectives are looking at people other than <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> declined to say whom. `` There always have been other people we have been checking out and there will be until there are no leads to follow.''
