<SECOND>AM-Aqueduct Repairs,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Repairing Storm-Ravaged LA Aqueduct Get Break From Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLANCHA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Workers repairing the flood-damaged aqueduct that supplies millions of Southern Californians with water got a break in the weather Sunday, but expected to be on the job two more weeks. Some 30 workers using bulldozers and other heavy equipment labored under sunny skies to scoop tons of mud, rocks and other storm debris out of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aqueduct </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Inyo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> about 180 miles north of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` They're continuing right along today, making good progress,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON>. A two-mile stretch of the aqueduct was buried when a flash flood hurled tons of debris down upon it Tuesday. Then a storm Thursday buckled a 1,000-foot stretch of the aqueduct's concrete lining. The aqueduct carries water from streams in the eastern <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> range to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and other <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> communities. Two 30-person teams were each working 12-hour shifts, and repairs were expected to take two weeks, the spokeswoman said. The city, which gets 75 percent of its water from the aqueduct, was n't expected to experience shortages in the meantime, but water officials urged residents to voluntarily conserve. A series of intense, widely scattered storms deluged parts of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, Imperial, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mono </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Inyo </LOCATION> counties throughout most of last week before moving into <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. Until the aqueduct is fixed, the water department will provide <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> with water by drawing supplies from reservoirs south of the broken part of the aqueduct and making extra purchases from the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON> said the damage was the worst since similar storms ravaged the aqueduct in 1968.
