<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Rock,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security, `Just Say Nyet' Buttons Frown on Drinking at Heavy Metal
Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet youth poured into <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to hear American heavy metal heroes Sunday but 10,000 security men and rockers with `` Just Say Nyet'' buttons kept the concert from getting too intoxicating. `` If the police were n't here, there would be drugs and drinking and making love,'' said <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Rvinskaya </PERSON>, an 18-year-old <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> mother dressed in the metal bracelets and tight, short blue-jean skirt favored by her motorcycle gang. `` But what can you do with police everywhere?'' she shrugged. And they were everywhere, among the 100,000 people gathered for the second day of ear-shattering heavy metal sounds from the likes of <LOCATION> Bon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jovi </LOCATION>, Scorpions and <ORGANIZATION> Ozzy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Osbourne </ORGANIZATION>. It was <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s biggest festival of foreign rock music, which for years was condemned as an infectious item of Western decadence. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> militia in blue, riot police in black, <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agents in dark civilian clothes and young toughs in uniform track suits and T-shirts lined the stage and aisles throughout the packed <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stadium </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Luzhniki </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>. Soviet impresario <PERSON> Stas </PERSON> <PERSON> Namin </PERSON> said he and the foreign organizers of the concert had requested the overwhelming security. He said Soviet authorities have never allowed so many young people to gather in one place, and they did n't know what to expect. Authorities might be suffer extra anxiety since the crowd came dressed in chains and skin-tight leather. <PERSON> Motley </PERSON> <PERSON> Crue </PERSON> incited the crowd to scream obscenities in English, which Soviet government television broadcast nationwide in its coverage of `` fragments'' of the concert. And some fans shed their clothes for a brief streak across the stands. But mountains of vodka bottles piled up outside the stadium, and suggestions of more outrageous behavior remained onstage. It was an appropriate action for a concert billed as an anti-drug and anti-alcohol event. Many rockers wore buttons emblazoned, `` Just Say Nyet.'' The audience poured into <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> from all over the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Oleg </PERSON> <PERSON> Galkin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Astrakhan </LOCATION> said he hitchhiked for 48 hours to reach the festival, and he does n't even like heavy metal. `` I would rather have heard Led <ORGANIZATION> Zeppelin </ORGANIZATION>, Dire Straits or <PERSON> Pink </PERSON> <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON>,'' he said. Hundreds of youths who could not afford the scalpers' price of up to $ 112 a ticket milled around outside the stadium. But no matter _ the music could be heard a half-mile away. Motorcycle gangs, rarely seen on the streets of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, showed off tattoos, brass knuckles and flags of the American Confederacy. They were joined by frumpy grandmothers and officials in business suits sitting stiffly in a stadium full of singing, screaming and dancing fans. Other rockers in the two-day festival, broadcast in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on pay television Sunday, were Cinderella and Skid Row from the West and Nuance and <LOCATION> Brigada </LOCATION> S from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
