<SECOND>AM-Wilderness Program,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Survival Program Faces Licensing, Legal Challenges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A wilderness survival program for troubled teens is fighting for its own life after running afoul of state officials and a teen-age girl who claims she was kidnapped and abused by the program's operators. Challenger Foundation II is designed to quell rebellious behavior and build confidence in teen-agers by forcing them to confront their problems in the setting of the rugged southern <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> desert. During their first three days in the desert, for example, they may eat only wild plants that they pick or animals and insects that they catch. The state attorney general's office says such a program amounts to therapy, which Challenger II lacks a license to provide. In addition, a judge has ruled that Challenger operators violated the civil rights of 17-year-old <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Zasso </PERSON> of Mt. <PERSON> Kisco </PERSON>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, by abducting her from a dentist's office and forcing her into the program at her father's request. Ms. <PERSON> Zasso </PERSON> is suing the program and its operators for $ 230 million, and a big award could put the school out of business. Challenger is threatened with further legal action from the state attorney general unless the operators can demonstrate that participating teens are provided adequate food, water and clothing, as well as such necessities as toilet paper and sleeping bags. Program founder <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cartisano </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> special forces sergeant billed in ads as a `` real-life Rambo,'' has filed a countersuit charging the state with harassment. Several state officials say they will decide this week whether Challenger must obtain a license as a therapeutic care provider to continue operation. Currently, the program's counselors do n't have the training required for such a license. <PERSON> Cartisano </PERSON>, who was in southern <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> over the weekend, did not return telephone calls to his office in <LOCATION> Provo </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Zasso </PERSON>'s attorneys did n't respond to a telephone request for comment. The company's ads promise that for $ 12,500 per teen, Challenger `` stops self-destructive behavior and places parents back in control.'' Its detractors say the 63-day survival program is cruel and dangerous. In the first stage of the program, the teens drink stream water they must purify with chemicals and substitute sagebrush for toilet paper. During the two latter stages, the participants' diet included oatmeal, lentils, cheese, meat, raisins and other foods provided by Challenger. During stage three, each 12-member group is given two wooden handcarts which they pull across about 130 miles of desert, emulating Mormon handcart pioneers who settled <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> in the 19th century. A graduate of the program, <PERSON> Krista </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, 15, of <LOCATION> Provo </LOCATION> said it helps youths overcome social and behavioral problems by building confidence and self esteem. `` It was n't my idea of a picnic. It was a hard program,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>. `` It helped me realize my potential, to see what I could do physically, emotionally and spiritually.'' She said that before her mother ordered her into the program last May, she was shy and lacked confidence. Now, she said she feels confident talking with strangers and peers, and she's confident that she can boost her grades beyond her current C-average She also believes she is better able to resist the temptation of drug abuse. Before the experience, `` My self-esteem was low enough I did n't think I was worth enough to say no I was headed for the drugs and alcohol.'' In her lawsuit, Ms. <PERSON> Zasso </PERSON> said she was working as a dental assistant in Mt. <PERSON> Kisco </PERSON> on June 15 when Challenger employees lured her into a dark hallway, subdued her and hustled her to a nearby airport for a flight to southern <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Zasso </PERSON> had left home to live with her boyfriend's family and had refused to return home. She said she was subjected to a strip search and then forced to walk as much as 18 miles at a time without food and clean water. The suit also alleges that she was denied medical treatment for a concussion. She remained in the program for 42 days until 3rd District Judge <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON>, who is considering the suit, found her rights had been violated and ordered her release. <PERSON> Zasso </PERSON> praised the program in a videotaped interview conducted by Challenger employees in the desert, but she later testified that she feared she would be forced repeat the program if she did n't tell the counselors what they wanted to hear
