<HEAD>GOP, Democrats Square Off in Race for Wright Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Republican physician was the highest vote-getter in a special election to replace <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but the Democrat who will face him in a runoff predicted victory in the heavily Democratic 12th District. Dr. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> garnered 21,978 ballots, or 39 percent of the vote, in Saturday's special election, but Democrat <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Geren </PERSON> was elated about his 32 percent showing _ 17,751 votes _ in the district that encompasses most of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Geren </PERSON> received a ringing endorsement from <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, who had expressed no favorite in the primary. `` I want to ask all of you to redouble your efforts because here's a man I want to be my successor,'' the popular <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> told supporters at a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> party for <PERSON> Geren </PERSON>. `` He is steeped in the traditions of our state and country.'' Democrat <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> finished third in the race with 22 percent of the vote, the only other candidate to garner more than 3 percent. `` Well, the Democrats won tonight,'' <PERSON> Geren </PERSON>, an attorney, told cheering supporters late Saturday. `` It took us four candidates to do it, but when you total it up, we got nearly 60 percent of the vote. I call that a victory.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> resigned the seat June 30 after an ethics investigation uncovered 69 instances of alleged house violations. In other election results, a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> government redistricting plan that supporters said would foster minority representation passed by a 2-to-1 margin. And <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> officials won a significant battle when voters in four of five <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> suburbs decided to retain the agency. Because no one in the eight-candidate race to replace <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> received a majority of the votes, a runoff is necessary. Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> will set a date after election results are certified. <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON>, host of a nationally syndicated TV health show, `` 60 Second Housecall,'' pointed to his success in a district traditionally dominated by Democrats, and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> in particular. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> first won election in 1955 and was re-elected 17 times in the next 34 years, often with token or no opposition. He received 88 write-in votes in Saturday's special election. However, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> carried the district in the last three presidential elections. `` Remember, now it's halftime,'' <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> told supporters Saturday night. `` Take a breather, go to church, come back on Monday and let's get after it.'' In an emotionally charged referendum, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> voters overwhelmingly approved a proposal to reorganize the city council, ostensibly to equalize voting power between whites and minorities. The proposal received 41,456 votes to 20,823 against. However, an analysis by The Dallas Morning News of voting patterns in Saturday's election showed that more than 85 percent of those who voted in the city's predominantly minority districts opposed the plan. The plan passed citywide because of overwhelming support from white voters. The so-called `` 10-4-1'' plan calls for the addition of two single districts and four quadrant representatives, leaving the mayor as the only at-large member of the city council. Opponents, who had their own plan, argued that adding seats would dilute minority strength. A lawsuit challenging the current 8-3 plan is scheduled to be heard Sept. 5 by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchmeyer </PERSON>, who also is reviewing the 10-4-1 plan. The five suburban elections were crucial to about one-fifth of the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> transit agency's sales tax income, and to the fate of a regional transportation system. Voters in <LOCATION> Carrollton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rowlett </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Plano </LOCATION> decided by margins of 59 percent or more to stay in DART. <PERSON> Coppell </PERSON> rejected <PERSON> DART </PERSON> by a 20-vote margin, but officials there said a recount is likely. In June, DART approved a $ 2.45 billion plan to crisscross the metropolitan area with 66 miles of light rail by 2010. The plan also called for 18 miles of rail connecting downtown to the <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and 37 miles of bus and car pool lanes for suburban commuters.
