 Israeli security forces and <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> militiamen captured a Lebanese man who allegedly assisted a suicide car bomb attack that wounded five <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers, the army said Sunday. The 28-year-old man, identified as a mercenary of the Moslem fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> group, was captured in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> on Wednesday, the day of the car bombing attack, but the army withheld the information until Sunday, an army statement said. The army would not give his name, and a military spokesman would not say if the man was being held by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> or <ORGANIZATION> SLA </ORGANIZATION> security forces. Five Israeli soldiers were wounded, one critically, when a car packed with 550 pounds of explosives blew up near a convoy of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> SLA </ORGANIZATION> troops. The Shiite Moslem group <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> claimed responsibility for the bombing and released a videotape showing the driver, Sheikh <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> <PERSON> Biro </PERSON>, who killed himself in the attack. There was no immediate word from <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> on the arrest. The army statement said the purported assistant was a resident of the village of <LOCATION> Markaba </LOCATION>, about a mile from the Israeli border. It said he was recruited by <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to organize attacks in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s self-declared security zone in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The alleged assistant let <PERSON> Biro </PERSON> stay the night before the bombing at his home in the security zone, the statement said. It said the two tried unsuccessfully to plant an explosive device that day. The man helped <PERSON> Biro </PERSON> get to the area where the car bomb detonated but was not in the car at the time, the army said. The security zone is a six - by 10-mile-wide strip in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> where <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> maintained a military force after the withdrawal of most of its troops from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1985 <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, is a fundamentalist Iranian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> faction in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> that is considered to be the umbrella organization for extremist groups holding foreign hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Sixteen foreigners are being held, including eight Americans.
