<HEAD>Rhode Island Victory Day Holiday Again Provokes Outcry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `Japan surrendered...,' to CORRECT date to May
sted March.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some Japanese-Americans are trying to change the name of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s Victory Day holiday because they say the popular name _ `` V-J Day'' for `` Victory in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'' _ is racist. The holiday Monday is still celebrated only in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, where by tradition it creates a long weekend when virtually everything shuts down and people head to the beach. This year, the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rhode </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> has hired lawyers to try to change the name. `` Unfortunately, the name Victory Day has caused persistent use of the appellation ` V-J Day' by the public, by the press, businesses, state offices,'' said one of the lawyers, <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> declined to say how the group might pursue a lawsuit, but said she has asked Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON>'s office to press for a name change or a way to force people to use the holiday's official name. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Connell </PERSON>, spokesman for <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON>, said the attorney general can not `` require the citizens of the state to call the holiday by a particular name.'' `` It's not the holiday itself that's bothering me. It's the name,'' said <PERSON> Hiromi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mineo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lima </PERSON>, 44, a <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> resident for 16 years. `` I feel a bit of discrimination against the Japanese race.'' <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> veterans' groups are adamant that the name should remain unchanged. `` Leave that ... holiday alone,'' said <PERSON> Lionel </PERSON> <PERSON> Poissant </PERSON>, state service officer for the <LOC