<HEAD>Nationalist Strikes Threatened in Three Republics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet authorities, dealing with a strike in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, face new work stoppages in the republics of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> over nationalist issues, union leaders said Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday that as many as 40,000 Russian-speaking workers in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> were striking to protest what they feel are discriminatory laws recently passed on preserving the Estonian language and limiting the voting rights of immigrants. Pravda sided with their demands. The People's Front of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> called a general strike Monday in `` non-strategic industries'' to demand local <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials move to a more democratic structure, said activist <PERSON> Aidin </PERSON> <PERSON> Amirbekov </PERSON> in a telephone interview. In <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, pro-independence activists had called for a general strike to begin Tuesday. There were conflicting reports on whether it would proceed. The ethnic Russian strikers in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> won support from a key source Sunday. Under the headline, `` And what about civil rights?'' Pravda charged that the new Estonian election law, which sets tough residency requirements, violates the Soviet constitutional equal rights provision. `` As is known, the Constitution has not yet been abandoned,'' Pravda said. The article criticized the Estonian lawmakers, who have led the call for human rights guarantees, for restricting the voting rights of non-Estonians. The new law limits voting to residents who have lived in the same district for two years or anywhere in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> for five years. Candidates must live in the same place for five years, or in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> for 10 years. A new language law requires most workers to learn Estonian. Many Russian workers have not, even after decades of living in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, and natives complain that many police and ambulance personnel can not understand their language. A <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> activist said workers in the <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION> demonstrated for a second night Sunday, but <PERSON> Amirbekov </PERSON>, speaking from the town, denied that report. <PERSON> Amirbekov </PERSON> said workers at manufacturing plants are being asked to strike Monday to support demands that local leaders `` find political solutions instead of military ones'' to the republic's ethnic violence, which has caused dozens of deaths He said workers in strategic industries, such as <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>'s extensive oil complex, were asked to stay on the job. Some activists in <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION> are demanding removal of Soviet troops from the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh and an end to curfews in the republic, but <PERSON> Amirbekov </PERSON> said authorities believe relations are too tense to consider that step. <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, which traditionally is Shiite Moslem, has been embroiled in a dispute with neighboring <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, whose population is mainly Christian, over control of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region. <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> is part of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, but its population is predominantly Armenian, and <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> wants to annex it. In <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, work has at least partially halted at 26 enterprises in the capital of <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION> and at 13 factories in <LOCATION> Kohtla-Jarve </LOCATION>, the labor newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Trud </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday. Train workers were on strike and the state airline <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> carried only emergency supplies and passengers, <PERSON> Trud </PERSON> said. The Russians, most of who work in heavy industrial plants, also object to a new national decision to give <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> and the two other Baltic republics, free rein over its economy. In asserting their rights, ethnic Estonians have angered immigrant workers from <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> and elsewhere. The workers are demanding that factories with a mainly Russian-speaking labor force remain the property of the national government rather than be handed over to <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Artur </PERSON> <PERSON> Kapityem </PERSON> at the Russians' strike headquarters in <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION> said by telephone that leaders were in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to meet with <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leaders since they have refused to negotiate with Estonian officials. `` We no longer trust the republic's leadership,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lysenko </PERSON> of the strike committee as saying. <PERSON> Kapityem </PERSON> denied Pravda's report that criminal charges had been filed against labor leaders under an emergency Estonian decree banning the strike. Ethnic Estonians make up slightly more than 60 percent of the population. Russians make up about a third of the 1.6 million people.
