<HEAD>Columbia Finishes Secret Military Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs, 8-9, `The landing ...,' with 6 grafs to UPDATE with
crew arrival in Houston, edit to conform; picks up 10th graf, `The shuttle's
...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos EAB1,3,5, LaserColor EAB1c</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The oldest space shuttle glided to a perfect landing in the <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> on Sunday, completing a secret mission to deploy a spy satellite and reportedly conduct `` Star Wars'' experiments. `` A super team and a great machine _ welcome home, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Culbertson </PERSON>, an astronaut from <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, said as the five-man crew landed shortly after sunrise, ending a five-day, one hour and 56-minute journey of more than 2 million miles. <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, though dirty, sustained little damage to the tiles that protect it from the heat of the fiery re-entry, and no tiles appeared to be missing, said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenner </PERSON>, shuttle support manager for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> at Edwards. It was the first mission in 3 -LCB- years for <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, which inaugurated shuttle flights in 1981. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s last flight ended 10 days before the January 1986 Challenger disaster that killed its crew of seven. `` It was an apparently perfect landing,'' observed <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovato </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` Welcome home, space cowboy!'' friends and relatives yelled at pilot <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> shortly before he and the other astronauts departed aboard two <LOCATION> Gulfstream </LOCATION> jets bound for <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> told a crowd of about 100 spectators that <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s mission represented `` a reaffirmation that human beings belong in space We can do wonderful things there. We can excite our kids and make our planet a better place to live.'' The astronauts and their wives arrived in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> around 4 p.m. CDT. They were greeted by their families and about 300 cheering friends and co-workers. `` It was a real privilege to participate in the restoration of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> to flight status,'' the shuttle's commander, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Col. <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, told the crowd at <LOCATION> Ellington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>. `` It was a privilege to accomplish what we accomplished on this flight for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' `` It was n't nice; it was fantastic,'' added <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> commander and one of three space rookies on the flight. After a 15-minute ceremony, the astronauts shook hands and hugged many of the well-wishers before climbing into vans and heading home with their families. The landing ended the 30th mission of the shuttle program. <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, for a years a `` hangar queen'' that was stripped of parts to keep other shuttles flying, had undergone more than 250 modifications called for after the Challenger disaster. The other crew members were <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Cmdr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Leestma </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> Lt. Col. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Col. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. The shuttle's sonic booms startled slumbering <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> as it hurtled across <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Minutes later, <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> guided the 97-ton orbiter to a 6:37 a.m. PDT landing on a hard clay runway, the aircraft trailing a plume of dust. A news blackout was imposed on the mission by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. But <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said Wednesday that a satellite was deployed by the astronauts during their first day in orbit on Tuesday. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> maintained the official silence about the satellite's purpose, but it is widely believed to be a 10-ton spy satellite designed to take detailed photographs of military targets over a wide area of the globe, including most of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> It would help the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> verify Soviet compliance with arms agreements. The shuttle crew also reportedly monitored military sites on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and was believed to have conducted experiments related to the `` Star Wars'' missile defense program. The shuttle landed in perfect weather, with unrestricted visibility. The few people gathered to watch on <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> also were treated to a view of the Perseid meteor shower, which sprinkled the sky with shooting stars. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> base 80 miles north of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> has been host to as many as half a million people for shuttle landings but was closed to the public Sunday because of the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s demand for secrecy. The news media were allowed to watch and record the landing from about two miles. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> said secrecy was needed to `` limit an adversary's ability to determine the mission of a given <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION> shuttle flight.''
