<HEAD>Fundamentalist Leader Released, Says He Is Under House Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fundamentalist Moslem preacher charged with anti-government activities has been released from jail, but he said Sunday he was under virtual house arrest. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON>, who is blind, was acquitted twice of charges connected to the assassination of President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> in October 1981. He and 48 other defendants now are being tried on charges of illegal possession of weapons, attempting to kill a police officer and assault. The charges are punishable by death. On Thursday, a state security court trying the 49 ordered the release of 25 prisoners, including <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON>. It ordered one defendant, who is charged with bombing a theater in the southern town of <LOCATION> Fayoum </LOCATION>, to remain in detention. The 23 others accused in the case had not been jailed. <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON>, contacted by telephone at his home in <LOCATION> Fayoum </LOCATION>, said, `` I'm in good health.'' He has high blood pressure and diabetes. `` There are security forces around my house,'' he said. `` They have stopped me from going out to pray at the mosque. They are not letting me out at all and are arresting my visitors.'' Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Wagih </PERSON> <PERSON> Issa </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> denied <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON>'s claims and said, `` He is free to move. Whoever wants to visit him may do so freely.'' The ministry, which is in charge of internal security, reportedly had invoked emergency regulations to extend the detention of the 25 who were released under the court order. <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON> returned to his home Friday night. The emergency law has been in force since <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>'s assassination. It gives police broad powers of search and arrest without charge and bans unauthorized demonstrations and strikes. <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON>, a former theology professor at <ORGANIZATION> Assiut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> south of <LOCATION> Fayoum </LOCATION>, heads a fundamentalist Moslem group that demands the immediate and full full implementation of the Islamic law, or <LOCATION> Sharia </LOCATION>. The government claims 90 percent of the existing law conforms to <LOCATION> Sharia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON> was accused of inspiring the gunmen who killed <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> and was acquitted. He also was found innocent in a later trial of 300 Moslem fundamentalists charged with an attempted coup after <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>'s assassination. In both cases, the prosecution said <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON> was the spiritual leader of an underground group called Jihad that was dedicated to the overthrow of the government. He was released in 1985 following the second acquittal. The current charges against him and 48 others involve an anti-government demonstration on April 7 that the prosecution claims <PERSON> Abdel-Rahman </PERSON> led. Police rounded up about 2,500 Moslem fundamentalists for questioning after the demonstration.
