<HEAD>Rite Aid Stockholder OK'd Pharmacy Panel Selection, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior aide to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> owned <ORGANIZATION> Rite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stock when he participated in the 1986 appointment of an executive of the drugstore chain to the state pharmacy board, The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday. The aide, <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON>, also was a guest of Rite Aid chairman <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Grass </PERSON> and his two sons, both company executives, on a January 1983 trip by corporate jet from <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> to watch <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> play in the <LOCATION> Sugar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bowl </LOCATION>, according to the newspaper. At the time, <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> was secretary of administration under then-Gov. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> is now assistant to the attorney general. Rite Aid, the nation's largest retail pharmacy chain, and its president, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grass </PERSON>, have been indicted in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> on state bribery charges. Grass, who is accused of delivering a $ 33,000 bribe and other benefits to a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmacy </ORGANIZATION>, is to be arraigned Tuesday. <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> said he was infuriated by implications in the Inquirer's story about his time in state government `` I did nothing improper according to the laws,'' <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> said in an interview Saturday night with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` I am truly offended.'' <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> owned 400 of 40 million shares in Rite Aid, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. Based on the stock's 1986 price range on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, his interest was worth between $ 9,700 and $ 14,200. `` That's not a very big stake in the company,'' <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON>, who also served in <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s gubernatorial administration, added that under <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> law, <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> did nothing improper. As secretary of administration, <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> was the key aide on appointments to state boards. He approved a recommendation that <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> name Rite Aid executive <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wendte </PERSON> to a seat on the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmacy </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> said. The governor went along with the recommendation on June 4, 1986. <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> said Saturday that he was aware of the appointment, but to insinuate that he had an effect on the decision was `` preposterous.'' He said he sold the stock in 1986, most likely toward the end of the year. <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> left <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s cabinet on Nov. 15, 1986 to accept a $ 100,000-a-year job as a senior vice president of the Harrisburg-based company. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s second term as governor ended in January 1987. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> accepted a seat on the Rite Aid board of directors in April 1987 and served until he became attorney general in August 1988. <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> left his Rite Aid job in November 1987 and joined <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> last August. He was not required to list the Rite Aid stock on disclosures filed publicly with the state <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and did not do so. He disclosed it within <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s administration on the more detailed reports required by the governor code of conduct. <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> called the 1983 Sugar Bowl trip `` a social call'' from his friend <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Grass </PERSON>, then a Rite Aid vice president. The trip was not disclosed although <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s code of conduct barred officials from accepting gifts or entertainment. <PERSON> Dickman </PERSON> said he cleared the trip with the governor's Office of General Counsel. `` It does n't appear that the legal advice was sound,'' <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> as having said Friday.
