<HEAD>Youth Dies of Gunshot Wound, Gaza Strip Workers Attacked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 16-year-old Palestinian died Sunday of wounds suffered in a clash with soldiers, and troops dispersed bands of masked youths attacking <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> workers applying for entry permits to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Arab hospital officials said 11 Palestinians were shot and wounded Sunday in clashes with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The death raised to 536 the number of Arabs killed in the 20-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories. Thirty-eight Israelis have been slain in the violence. Also Sunday, one of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s leading religious figures said that under Jewish law, the concept of preserving Jewish lives took precedence over all other commandments, including settling the biblical land of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. But Rabbi <PERSON> Ovadia </PERSON> <PERSON> Yosef </PERSON> of the ultraorthodox <ORGANIZATION> Shas </ORGANIZATION> political party did not make the anticipated religious ruling on returning territories to preserve Jewish lives. He said relinquishing territories at this time is not realistic because there is no <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> partner for peace. Jewish settlers living in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> claim there is a religious imperative for them to settle there. <PERSON> Yosef </PERSON>, addressing an assembly of about 1,000 ultraorthodox Jews in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, did not retract his statement made to <LOCATION> Egyptian </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> last month that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> could return territories to avoid loss of lives in a war. Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>, speaking at the same assembly, said he favored territorial compromise so <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> could maintain a Jewish majority in its own state. `` Between claiming our right to the -LRB- biblical -RRB- land of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> _ and I do n't doubt that right _ and losing the Jewishness of the state ... I want a Jewish state within its own borders with the Jewish traditions,'' he said. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>'s left-leaning Labor party favors territorial compromise while Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc is opposed. The latest Palestinian to die in the uprising was <PERSON> Fayez </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Obeid </PERSON>, 16. The army said he was shot during a clash with troops Saturday at the <LOCATION> Rafah </LOCATION> refugee camp in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, and he died at <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hashomer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. Also in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, a 32-year-old taxi driver, <PERSON> Mustafa </PERSON> <PERSON> Darwish </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Dahrouj </PERSON>, was fatally shot Saturday, and <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> sources said he was killed because it was believed he collaborated with with Israeli authorities. He was the 95th Palestinian killed by fellow <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> as a suspected collaborator. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers fired tear gas and rubber bullets at youths throwing stones at about 5,000 Palestinian workers applying for entry permits near the <LOCATION> Erez </LOCATION> crossing in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, Arab witnesses said. An army spokesman said troopers dispersed rioters but no one was injured seriously. He would not say if tear gas and rubber bullets were used. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, in an effort to limit the uprising, is requiring all Palestinians with jobs in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to have entry permits. Both <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and leaders of the uprising are trying to control the workers' movements. A military official said the fighting at <LOCATION> Erez </LOCATION> began after officials turned away hundreds of people from an application office because of the large number of workers waiting. The office has been handling up to 1,000 applicants daily. About 50,000 Gazans work in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and for many families their jobs are the only income. The military official said about 40,000 permits have been issued.
