<HEAD>Five Volunteer Firefighters Charged With Setting Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five volunteer firefighters and a sixth person have been arrested and charged with setting 16 fires, a newspaper reported Sunday. The arrests Friday grew out of an investigation by police and the arson squad of the <LOCATION> Bergen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Prosecutor's Office into 50 suspicious fires, according to The Record of <LOCATION> Hackensack </LOCATION>. The 16 fires occurred in a railroad boxcar, trash bins, brush and abandoned mattresses between January 1988 and last June. No one was injured. The prosecutor's office said the fires `` were started by the five borough firemen and one juvenile female who enjoyed watching her boyfriend fight the arson blaze.'' There was no other indication of motive. The six were charged in <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rutherford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> with failure to report or control dangerous fires, the Record reported. All but the juvenile, whose name police did not release, were charged with criminal mischief. Four of the people charged were released on their own recognizance. <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Dechert </PERSON>, 21, and <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillies </PERSON>, 20, were also charged with arson. <PERSON> Dechert </PERSON> was released on $ 50,000 bail. <PERSON> Gillies </PERSON> was released on $ 20,000 bail, the Record said. Also charged were <PERSON> Dechert </PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>, 18, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivelli </PERSON>, 19, and <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, 20. The five volunteer firefighters were to be suspended from the <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rutherford </ORGANIZATION> department until the outcome of their cases, Fire Chief <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Klamerus </PERSON> told the Record.
