<HEAD>Former Border Guard Says Majority of Troopers Ignored Orders To Shoot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto BER8</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Berlin Wall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For more than a year platoon leader <PERSON> Falk </PERSON> <PERSON> Turba </PERSON> patrolled the border between <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, his automatic rifle at the ready to stop anyone attempting to flee to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. In July, he slipped away from his comrades, tossed his rifle aside and scrambled over the barbed-wire and concrete barriers to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` I just could n't take it anymore,'' <PERSON> Turba </PERSON> said in an interview in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> on Sunday, the 28th anniversary of the building of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall. <LOCATION> Turba </LOCATION>, 20, spoke of the daily life of communist <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s elite border troopers _ young men selected by <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and military officials because of their loyality to the state <PERSON> Turba </PERSON>, who grew up in <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION>, said border guards were told in April that a shoot-to-kill order against civilians trying to flee <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> had been lifted. But he said most of his comrades had quietly ignored the order during their border service. `` Only about 10 percent of the hard-core, gung-ho troops would shoot at an unarmed civilian attempting to flee,'' <PERSON> Turba </PERSON> said. `` They're the macho types who like strutting around with their machine guns looking tough.'' But he said it was a great risk for the border guards to allow someone to escape. `` If you let someone escape, you go to prison,'' he said. `` It's also very risky because you patrol in pairs, and you never know what the other guy is thinking or what he would do `` But I hoped, and many others did as well, that I would never have to arrest someone.'' He said electronic listening devices and alarm systems, attack dogs and rows of barbed-wire usually slowed would-be escapees long enough that border troops could arrest them. Many of those caught were given long prison terms. According to West German statistics, 191 people have been killed trying to escape since the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall was erected in 1961 and the border between the two Germanies was sealed by barriers. But about 218,000 people managed to escape including 2,614 border troops, according to the statistics. <PERSON> Turba </PERSON> said he decided to flee because he had little hope of political and economic changes in his country. Unlike <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, where reform communists have succeeded in expanding freedoms, East German leader <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON> maintains a hard-line policy. <PERSON> Turba </PERSON> said a growing number of border guards are openly questioning the nation's border policy, which East German officials contend is necessary `` to protect socialism from Western plunderers.'' `` You sit in your freezing bunker or guard tower and begin to ask yourself what this border is for and what you are doing,'' <PERSON> Turba </PERSON> said. `` You reach a point where you realize its senseless and brutal.'' He said morale among border units is slumping because the increasing number of escape attempts brings additional pressure from their officers. Frustration and disillusionment lead many troopers to break regulations, according to <LOCATION> Turba </LOCATION>. `` Some people bring books to read in the towers. Others rig their field radios to tune into Western broadcasts. The political officer once took off to go hunting,'' he said. On July 12, <PERSON> Turba </PERSON> told his comrades he had problems with his motorcycle and he needed to take it for a test drive. He roared over a hill, coasted to the border barriers and bounded to freedom. `` There are a lot of weak points along the border and we know them best,'' he said.
