<HEAD>Lightning Adds To Woes, But Idaho Firefighters Holding Own</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Firefighters hustled to stamp out dozens of small fires ignited by lightning Sunday, but held their own against major forest and range fires that have scorched about 91,000 acres. Brief thunderstorms helped keep major fires from growing, but the lightning that accompanied them sparked nearly 100 new outbreaks in the <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Payette </PERSON> national forests alone, officials said. Firefighters who parachuted into affected areas and firefighting aircraft put out most of the new fires before they burned more than an acre, said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> fire information officer <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Tocco </PERSON>. In the <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> in central <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, firefighters moved closer to containing a 45,524-acre fire and a 20,380-acre blaze. The two fires were 90 percent contained by Sunday afternoon, and officials projected full containment by Monday evening. Firefighters were having less success with two fires that have scorched 13,300 acres in <ORGANIZATION> Payette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. The fires had combined by Sunday to form one larger fire. Efforts to contain it were augmented by two <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blackhawk </ORGANIZATION> helicopters that ferried firefighters to isolated edges of the blaze. More than 6,500 firefighters and 1,400 military personnel have battled 10 major fires in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> during recent weeks.
