<HEAD>Norwegian Trawler Nets Unmarked Submarine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROMSOE, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Norwegian trawler caught an unmarked submarine in its fishing net but the sub's crew used axes and blowtorches to cut the vessel free and it fled without identifying itself, a news report said Sunday. The trawler <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> was fishing Saturday near <LOCATION> Bear </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, 250 miles off of northern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, when the submarine ran into its nets, dragging the <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> backward, the ship's owner <PERSON> Jens-Petter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kraknes </PERSON> told the Norwegian news agency <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION>. It reported <PERSON> Kraknes </PERSON> said he decided not to release the submarine unless it identified itself and the sub surfaced quickly. The submarine crewemen refused to identify their craft and instead used axes, blowtocrhes and sledgehammers to cut away the net, <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> said. In about an hour the sub was freed and sailed away, <PERSON> Kraknes </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION>. His report said the Orion fishermen saw no markings on the vessel, which was in international waters, but they took photographs of the vessel and they will be sent to <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s Northern Defense Command <PERSON> Arild </PERSON> <PERSON> Isegg </PERSON> of the Norwegian <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> he was `` just about positive'' there were no submarines from the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> in the area, which is used by both <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and Soviet vessels.
